WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.750 --> 00:00:06.683
Prof: What I'm planning
to do today is to spend a half

00:00:06.683 --> 00:00:10.683
an hour or less just telling you
a little bit about what a new

00:00:10.683 --> 00:00:13.832
theory might be,
what I call the Leverage Cycle,

00:00:13.832 --> 00:00:17.262
and then spend the rest of the
time maybe answering questions

00:00:17.262 --> 00:00:19.550
about the course that you might
have.

00:00:19.550 --> 00:00:22.104
I could, if you wanted to,
devote the whole time to what

00:00:22.104 --> 00:00:24.773
the new theory is,
but why don't I at least pause

00:00:24.773 --> 00:00:27.710
after a half an hour and see if
you have questions?

00:00:27.710 --> 00:00:32.572
So what is the thing that's
been missing from the entire

00:00:32.572 --> 00:00:37.170
course and has been missing from
economic theory,

00:00:37.170 --> 00:00:41.290
I think, almost entirely for
all these years,

00:00:41.290 --> 00:00:44.791
and certainly missing from all
the textbooks that you might

00:00:44.791 --> 00:00:47.930
have looked at during the course
of the semester,

00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:50.259
and you remember there was a
list of 20 books or something

00:00:50.259 --> 00:00:53.328
you could have read,
and that's the idea of

00:00:53.328 --> 00:00:54.490
collateral.
 

00:00:54.490 --> 00:00:58.479
It's the idea that in order to
guarantee that you're going to

00:00:58.479 --> 00:01:01.868
keep your promise you have to
put up collateral,

00:01:01.868 --> 00:01:05.072
and people just don't trust in
everyone else keeping their

00:01:05.072 --> 00:01:07.349
promise,
they want collateral.

00:01:07.349 --> 00:01:11.790
So if you put that into the
model what sorts of things might

00:01:11.790 --> 00:01:12.920
be different?
 

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:15.552
So I want to just work out an
example so you can see how they

00:01:15.552 --> 00:01:16.209
might change.
 

00:01:16.209 --> 00:01:20.242
I want to talk about an example
that's going to illustrate what

00:01:20.242 --> 00:01:21.870
happened in our crisis.
 

00:01:21.870 --> 00:01:25.513
And I guess that it's a little
interesting that I wrote this

00:01:25.513 --> 00:01:28.849
and I presented this in 2000 at
the World Congress,

00:01:28.849 --> 00:01:32.605
and it got published in 2003,
so this was long before the

00:01:32.605 --> 00:01:33.209
crisis.
 

00:01:33.209 --> 00:01:36.769
Now, as I said,
there had been other smaller

00:01:36.769 --> 00:01:40.985
crises before in 1998,
maybe '94, maybe '87,

00:01:40.985 --> 00:01:43.920
certainly '98,
and of course I was thinking

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:46.430
about these previous crises when
I built this model,

00:01:46.430 --> 00:01:50.010
but not many other people
thought much of those other

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:50.629
crises.
 

00:01:50.629 --> 00:01:53.354
And as it happens,
this last one that we're still

00:01:53.354 --> 00:01:55.927
at the bottom of,
or a little past the bottom of,

00:01:55.927 --> 00:01:58.340
I think is very similar to the
ones we had before,

00:01:58.340 --> 00:02:00.590
but just much bigger.
 

00:02:00.590 --> 00:02:03.010
So here's my simple version of
it.

00:02:03.010 --> 00:02:05.560
I'm going to give two models,
a very simple one with two

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:08.016
periods and a slightly more
complicated one with three

00:02:08.016 --> 00:02:09.552
periods,
and of course all the

00:02:09.552 --> 00:02:11.908
interesting things happen in the
three-period case,

00:02:11.908 --> 00:02:14.716
but just to make it simple to
understand I'm starting with the

00:02:14.716 --> 00:02:15.360
simpler one.
 

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:20.808
So suppose that there's a
security which I'm going to call

00:02:20.808 --> 00:02:23.199
Y that everybody holds.
 

00:02:23.199 --> 00:02:26.750
Why is there no chalk?
 

00:02:26.750 --> 00:02:30.030
Gosh, I taught the class in
here, I just finished lecturing

00:02:30.030 --> 00:02:32.235
in here with a whole box,
oh here it is,

00:02:32.235 --> 00:02:33.650
a whole box of chalk.
 

00:02:33.650 --> 00:02:39.015
So suppose that there's a
security Y that I'm going to

00:02:39.015 --> 00:02:44.205
think of as a mortgage security,
or you could think of it as a

00:02:44.205 --> 00:02:46.497
house,
or you could think of it as an

00:02:46.497 --> 00:02:49.870
oil well that has uncertain
output in the next period.

00:02:49.870 --> 00:02:52.979
And then there's going to be
something like gold that I'll

00:02:52.979 --> 00:02:53.470
call X.
 

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:58.952
So this might be like gold,
and this might be like a

00:02:58.952 --> 00:03:02.841
mortgage security,
or like an oil well,

00:03:02.841 --> 00:03:05.938
or you might think of it as a
house,

00:03:05.938 --> 00:03:07.289
but I'll think of a mortgage
security,

00:03:07.289 --> 00:03:08.158
an oil well.
 

00:03:08.158 --> 00:03:11.810
It's something that pays an
uncertain outcome in the future,

00:03:11.810 --> 00:03:14.882
and this is something that's
very stable and you know exactly

00:03:14.882 --> 00:03:18.195
you've got gold this period,
if you just save it you'll have

00:03:18.195 --> 00:03:19.699
the same gold next period.
 

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:22.115
So now people are going to
differ according to how

00:03:22.115 --> 00:03:23.938
optimistic or pessimistic they
are.

00:03:23.938 --> 00:03:26.930
That's my idea of,
not everybody's the same.

00:03:26.930 --> 00:03:31.120
So I imagine that there are two
possibilities next period.

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:33.774
Either the Y,
the oil well,

00:03:33.774 --> 00:03:37.960
could produce--it's a gold-well
really.

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:41.116
It could produce 2 pieces of
gold, I mean,

00:03:41.116 --> 00:03:44.272
1 piece of gold,
or it could produce .2,20

00:03:44.272 --> 00:03:46.660
percent of a piece of gold.
 

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:49.960
So everybody begins with 1 oil
well,

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:52.770
1 mortgage security and 1 piece
of gold,

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:56.461
so they can consume the gold or
they can make it a filling for

00:03:56.461 --> 00:03:58.651
their teeth,
or they can wait next period

00:03:58.651 --> 00:04:01.304
and then they'd have it in
either state next period because

00:04:01.304 --> 00:04:05.306
it's perfectly durable,
or they could use the gold to

00:04:05.306 --> 00:04:10.669
buy more oil wells,
each of which might pay off 1

00:04:10.669 --> 00:04:11.479
or .2.
 

00:04:11.479 --> 00:04:12.810
So that's it.
 

00:04:12.810 --> 00:04:14.680
Now people care about the
consumption of gold.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:16.220
The only reason to get the oil
well,

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:19.069
as Fisher, as we've assumed all
through the class,

00:04:19.069 --> 00:04:21.774
the only reason to get the oil
well is that it might produce

00:04:21.774 --> 00:04:26.079
gold for you next period,
gushing oil, money, gold.

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:28.660
It might gush some gold for you
next period.

00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:31.767
So people care about
consumption, how much gold they

00:04:31.767 --> 00:04:33.855
eat here,
times the probability that

00:04:33.855 --> 00:04:36.654
they're going to be up here,
times how much they eat here,

00:04:36.654 --> 00:04:39.209
plus the probability that
they're going to come down here,

00:04:39.209 --> 00:04:40.350
times how much they eat here.
 

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:43.742
In other words they are risk
neutral with no discounting and

00:04:43.742 --> 00:04:46.619
they just multiply consumption
here and here by the

00:04:46.619 --> 00:04:49.149
probabilities and add the
consumptions,

00:04:49.149 --> 00:04:50.930
and then add it to the
consumption here.

00:04:50.930 --> 00:04:53.264
Everybody's got the same
utility, but with one

00:04:53.264 --> 00:04:53.940
difference.
 

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:59.959
H is the probability agent H
attaches to going up.

00:04:59.959 --> 00:05:03.290
So I think of these people as a
continuum of buyers now.

00:05:03.290 --> 00:05:05.459
Instead of 2 buyers like we've
always had,

00:05:05.459 --> 00:05:07.309
or 3 buyers,
or even 1 buyer ,

00:05:07.309 --> 00:05:10.752
I've got a continuum and
they're different because some

00:05:10.752 --> 00:05:13.050
are more optimistic than others.
 

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:15.369
Now, this is stuff that we
haven't really paid much

00:05:15.369 --> 00:05:16.389
attention to before.
 

00:05:16.389 --> 00:05:19.303
So these optimists are the
people who have H very close to

00:05:19.303 --> 00:05:21.317
1,
and lots of other people have

00:05:21.317 --> 00:05:23.689
Hs in the middle,
and there are some people who

00:05:23.689 --> 00:05:24.279
think H is 0.
 

00:05:24.279 --> 00:05:26.250
That's the way they differ.
 

00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:29.298
So of course the very most
optimistic person thinks the oil

00:05:29.298 --> 00:05:30.980
well is worth 1 piece of gold.
 

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:33.879
He doesn't discount,
and he thinks he's going to get

00:05:33.879 --> 00:05:36.949
1 for sure, so he'd be willing
to pay 1 for it here.

00:05:36.949 --> 00:05:40.031
The most pessimistic person
thinks the oil well is only

00:05:40.031 --> 00:05:40.660
worth .2.
 

00:05:40.660 --> 00:05:45.420
And let's say she'd only be
willing to pay .2 for it here.

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:49.300
So what's the price of oil
wells going to be?

00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:55.180
Well, if we just had our usual
model,

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:58.283
a one period model,
we would see that the people

00:05:58.283 --> 00:06:02.115
with the high H would sell their
gold to buy more oil wells

00:06:02.115 --> 00:06:05.220
because they thought it would be
valuable,

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:08.148
and the people with the low Hs,
thinking the oil wells weren't

00:06:08.148 --> 00:06:10.850
worth much,
would sell them to the high H

00:06:10.850 --> 00:06:13.649
people to get more gold in the
present.

00:06:13.649 --> 00:06:16.610
That's basically what would
happen.

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:20.499
And you'd get some dividing
line where the people above A

00:06:20.499 --> 00:06:24.250
would be buying oil wells,
spending all their money.

00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:28.269
And the people below A would be
selling oil wells and getting

00:06:28.269 --> 00:06:29.139
more money.
 

00:06:29.139 --> 00:06:31.083
So, for example,
if A was .69,

00:06:31.083 --> 00:06:33.898
which is what it's going to
turn out to be,

00:06:33.898 --> 00:06:37.920
Mr. A, what does he think the
value of an oil well is?

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:46.997
He thinks it's .69 times 1 .31
times .2 which is .06,

00:06:46.997 --> 00:06:50.490
so .69 .06 is .75.
 

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:51.370
So Mr.
 

00:06:51.370 --> 00:06:57.389
69 thinks the oil well's worth
about 75.

00:06:57.389 --> 00:07:00.180
Everyone above him thinks it's
worth more than 75,

00:07:00.180 --> 00:07:04.190
so if the price were .75
everyone above would want to buy

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:08.415
and everyone below would say
it's not worth .75 so I'll sell

00:07:08.415 --> 00:07:10.836
it,
and since they're risk neutral

00:07:10.836 --> 00:07:14.528
their valuation is independent
of how much of it they have.

00:07:14.528 --> 00:07:16.889
So these people below would
want to sell everything,

00:07:16.889 --> 00:07:19.389
and these people above would
want to buy everything.

00:07:19.389 --> 00:07:22.011
So that's nothing different
from what we've done from the

00:07:22.011 --> 00:07:24.819
very beginning except that maybe
the one difference is people

00:07:24.819 --> 00:07:26.129
would go to the extreme.
 

00:07:26.129 --> 00:07:29.331
These guys would spend all
their money buying oil wells

00:07:29.331 --> 00:07:32.829
because every time they bought
an oil well at a price of .75

00:07:32.829 --> 00:07:34.314
this guy,
for example,

00:07:34.314 --> 00:07:35.569
was sure it's worth 1.
 

00:07:35.569 --> 00:07:37.199
The more he buys the better he
is.

00:07:37.199 --> 00:07:39.968
So he'd spend all his money in
oil wells and these guys would

00:07:39.968 --> 00:07:42.459
sell all their oil wells,
but other than that it's very

00:07:42.459 --> 00:07:43.889
similar to what we've done.
 

00:07:43.889 --> 00:07:47.279
So what's the difference going
to be?

00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:51.000
The difference is just one
thing.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.079
Where do I divide this dividing
line A?

00:07:54.079 --> 00:07:57.990
Well, can these guys up here
afford to buy all these oil

00:07:57.990 --> 00:07:58.560
wells?
 

00:07:58.560 --> 00:08:00.795
Well, the answer is,
so far, it doesn't look like

00:08:00.795 --> 00:08:03.617
that's possible,
because if the dividing line is

00:08:03.617 --> 00:08:07.370
way up here these guys up here
don't have enough money to buy

00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:09.310
all the oil wells down here.
 

00:08:09.310 --> 00:08:12.874
After all, they only have 1
piece of gold apiece and if the

00:08:12.874 --> 00:08:16.069
oil well costs 75 they can each
buy 1 and 1 third.

00:08:16.069 --> 00:08:19.716
If you multiply that by 1 and 1
third you're never going to buy

00:08:19.716 --> 00:08:21.600
all these oil wells down here.
 

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:26.110
So this seems like it's too
high for A to be.

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:30.601
So the new twist is,
maybe the guys up here who want

00:08:30.601 --> 00:08:33.355
the oil wells,
who are so sure they're going

00:08:33.355 --> 00:08:35.922
to do well,
maybe they can borrow money to

00:08:35.922 --> 00:08:37.190
buy the oil wells.
 

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:40.808
So they can make a promise to
pay money in the future,

00:08:40.808 --> 00:08:45.168
maybe .5 and .5 in the future,
say,

00:08:45.168 --> 00:08:49.668
and then sell those promises,
borrow money in other words,

00:08:49.668 --> 00:08:53.357
promising in the future,
and then use that money to buy

00:08:53.357 --> 00:08:54.519
more oil wells.
 

00:08:54.519 --> 00:08:56.058
So that's what people do in the
market.

00:08:56.058 --> 00:08:59.004
Any hedge fund,
the three definitions of a

00:08:59.004 --> 00:09:00.716
hedge fund,
the three defining

00:09:00.716 --> 00:09:04.312
characteristics of a hedge fund,
I think I might have said once,

00:09:04.312 --> 00:09:05.933
are,
a) that they hedge,

00:09:05.933 --> 00:09:09.860
so unlike other money managers
they're always trying to hedge.

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:11.149
And we talked about what
hedging is.

00:09:11.149 --> 00:09:14.190
And many, many more managers
are doing that than ever before.

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:18.519
It's different from 50 percent
of the people,

00:09:18.519 --> 00:09:21.304
but not from,
you know, the hedge funds are 5

00:09:21.304 --> 00:09:24.659
percent and the other 45 percent
are also hedging,

00:09:24.659 --> 00:09:25.629
so that's not so different.
 

00:09:25.629 --> 00:09:29.092
The second thing they do is
they borrow money to make their

00:09:29.092 --> 00:09:29.928
investments.
 

00:09:29.928 --> 00:09:32.070
A lot of these other managers
aren't allowed to borrow.

00:09:32.070 --> 00:09:35.190
They may not be allowed to
hedge either.

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:37.289
Those are called long only
managers.

00:09:37.289 --> 00:09:38.159
They can't hedge.
 

00:09:38.159 --> 00:09:40.230
Some of them can't borrow.
 

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:44.437
Hedge funds hedge and borrow,
and then hedge funds charge

00:09:44.437 --> 00:09:45.340
high fees.
 

00:09:45.340 --> 00:09:47.429
That's the third defining
characteristic.

00:09:47.429 --> 00:09:48.798
But anyway, so they borrow.
 

00:09:48.798 --> 00:09:51.615
And in the economy,
I told you last time,

00:09:51.615 --> 00:09:55.700
a huge number of people
borrowed a huge amount of money.

00:09:55.700 --> 00:09:57.580
So borrowing is obviously very
important.

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:00.080
So how much are they going to
be able to borrow?

00:10:00.080 --> 00:10:02.712
I mean, this guy,
number one, he'd like to borrow

00:10:02.712 --> 00:10:03.918
as much as he could.
 

00:10:03.918 --> 00:10:07.374
Every time he borrows money
he's sure that he's going to be

00:10:07.374 --> 00:10:09.197
up here,
so every time he borrows 1

00:10:09.197 --> 00:10:11.577
dollar he gets to make an
investment that he's sure is

00:10:11.577 --> 00:10:14.629
going to be a great investment,
and he's planning on paying

00:10:14.629 --> 00:10:17.808
everything back because he's
sure he's going to go here,

00:10:17.808 --> 00:10:19.528
so he's going to be incredibly
rich.

00:10:19.528 --> 00:10:22.272
So he's going to pay back what
he borrows, but he's going to

00:10:22.272 --> 00:10:24.548
get such a profit he's going to
make a fortune.

00:10:24.548 --> 00:10:27.080
So if people could borrow
however much they wanted to,

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:29.794
and promise to payback,
this guy would borrow

00:10:29.794 --> 00:10:30.812
everything,
Mr.

00:10:30.812 --> 00:10:33.465
1, I mean, would borrow
everything and imagine he was

00:10:33.465 --> 00:10:36.332
going to get up here for sure,
and imagine he was going to

00:10:36.332 --> 00:10:42.643
keep his promise for sure,
and he bid the price up almost

00:10:42.643 --> 00:10:43.668
to 1.
 

00:10:43.668 --> 00:10:46.619
But now, who's going to lend to
him and how much will they

00:10:46.619 --> 00:10:47.808
actually lend to him?
 

00:10:47.808 --> 00:10:51.986
Well, in our old world we
didn't worry about who was going

00:10:51.986 --> 00:10:52.720
to lend.
 

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:55.147
Everybody assumed they were
going to get paid back,

00:10:55.147 --> 00:10:58.011
but in reality people don't
assume they're going to get paid

00:10:58.011 --> 00:10:58.450
back.
 

00:10:58.450 --> 00:10:59.830
The lenders are going to say to
themselves,

00:10:59.830 --> 00:11:02.865
"Wait a minute,
if this guy promises us to pay

00:11:02.865 --> 00:11:05.341
us,
say, .5 and .5 maybe he'll be

00:11:05.341 --> 00:11:09.350
very rich over here and he'll be
able to pay us back,

00:11:09.350 --> 00:11:12.269
but I'm not sure he's going to
be so rich here.

00:11:12.269 --> 00:11:14.519
I don't even know what he has.
 

00:11:14.519 --> 00:11:17.359
How do I know what the borrower
is going to actually have in

00:11:17.359 --> 00:11:18.370
these states?"
 

00:11:18.370 --> 00:11:21.971
I don't want to look into his
personal bank account and find

00:11:21.971 --> 00:11:23.620
out everything about him.
 

00:11:23.620 --> 00:11:26.201
That's the way,
banks who lend sometimes do

00:11:26.201 --> 00:11:29.767
that and they go to a lot of
effort to check how reliable a

00:11:29.767 --> 00:11:32.820
borrower you are,
but people in general,

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:36.139
most of the lenders,
you don't want to do that.

00:11:36.139 --> 00:11:37.899
That was the idea of
securitization.

00:11:37.899 --> 00:11:41.837
We don't have to have so much
careful looking into the

00:11:41.837 --> 00:11:44.288
personal finances of everybody.
 

00:11:44.288 --> 00:11:49.918
Much simpler is to use the
asset Y as collateral.

00:11:49.918 --> 00:11:52.210
So if Y is collateral,
what does that mean?

00:11:52.210 --> 00:11:55.505
When you lend 1 dollar to a
borrower the borrower just

00:11:55.505 --> 00:11:58.990
doesn't borrow the dollar
promising to pay something back

00:11:58.990 --> 00:12:00.110
in the future.
 

00:12:00.110 --> 00:12:03.171
The borrower says,
"if I don't pay you back

00:12:03.171 --> 00:12:05.190
you can take the asset."
 

00:12:05.190 --> 00:12:09.642
So the question is,
for each unit of the asset Y,

00:12:09.642 --> 00:12:14.187
how much can you borrow when
you have the asset as

00:12:14.187 --> 00:12:15.580
collateral?
 

00:12:15.580 --> 00:12:18.090
That's the question of leverage.
 

00:12:18.090 --> 00:12:27.267
So if you take the value of Y
divided by the cash down--so

00:12:27.267 --> 00:12:30.970
let's do two numbers.
 

00:12:30.970 --> 00:12:37.597
So the borrowed,
dollars borrowed using Y as

00:12:37.597 --> 00:12:47.154
collateral, that divided by the
value of Y, that's what we call

00:12:47.154 --> 00:12:53.629
the loan to value,
LTV, loan to value.

00:12:53.629 --> 00:12:58.299
Another way of saying that is
the borrowed,

00:12:58.299 --> 00:13:02.303
if you take Y,
dollar Y minus dollars

00:13:02.303 --> 00:13:08.308
borrowed, that--let's write it
in the denominator.

00:13:08.308 --> 00:13:16.836
Dollar Y minus dollars
borrowed, and here you put value

00:13:16.836 --> 00:13:23.308
of Y, so just dollar Y,
in other words.

00:13:23.308 --> 00:13:25.816
The dollar of Y minus the
dollar borrowed,

00:13:25.816 --> 00:13:28.139
that's the cash you had to put
down.

00:13:28.139 --> 00:13:34.070
So that's the dollar of Y
divided by the cash down.

00:13:34.070 --> 00:13:45.700
That's what's called leverage.
 

00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:49.061
So, and it's obviously the same
thing as loan to value because

00:13:49.061 --> 00:13:52.091
you just sort of invert the
number and do a subtraction,

00:13:52.091 --> 00:13:53.250
you get leverage.
 

00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:55.763
So if you knew the loan to
value you'd know the leverage

00:13:55.763 --> 00:13:56.539
and vice versa.
 

00:13:56.539 --> 00:13:57.720
They're the same thing.
 

00:13:57.720 --> 00:14:00.308
So what should the loan to
value be?

00:14:00.308 --> 00:14:03.671
