00:30:11.834 --> 00:30:15.256
well,
and I'm going to make a profit

00:30:15.256 --> 00:30:16.420
of 33 percent.
 

00:30:16.420 --> 00:30:22.808
My .75 is going to turn into 1
for sure, so why isn't that just

00:30:22.808 --> 00:30:26.210
a brilliant thing for me to do?
 

00:30:26.210 --> 00:30:28.740
Why should I be satisfied?
 

00:30:28.740 --> 00:30:33.688
The more oil wells I get my
hands on the better I seem to

00:30:33.688 --> 00:30:34.660
do."
 

00:30:34.660 --> 00:30:37.920
So why is he not making the
(.3, .3) promise?

00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:41.153
So it sounds like he ought to,
but if you think about it one

00:30:41.153 --> 00:30:43.730
more minute you'll realize that
he shouldn't.

00:30:43.730 --> 00:30:46.790
And why is that,
because he could promise (.2,

00:30:46.790 --> 00:30:47.200
.2).
 

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:50.098
So if he makes the (.3,
.3) promise of course he has to

00:30:50.098 --> 00:30:52.905
give up the (.2,
.2) promise because the oil

00:30:52.905 --> 00:30:55.618
well he used as collateral for
the (.3,

00:30:55.618 --> 00:30:58.768
.3) promise he no longer has
available for the (.2,

00:30:58.768 --> 00:30:59.650
.2) promise.
 

00:30:59.650 --> 00:31:02.989
So the question isn't,
should he do a (.3,

00:31:02.989 --> 00:31:04.130
.3) promise.
 

00:31:04.130 --> 00:31:06.132
Well, if that was the only
thing he could do of course he

00:31:06.132 --> 00:31:07.609
would do that,
so of course it looks

00:31:07.609 --> 00:31:10.140
profitable, but he's already got
a great profit opportunity.

00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:12.369
The question is,
is it a better profit

00:31:12.369 --> 00:31:14.480
opportunity and the answer is
no.

00:31:14.480 --> 00:31:15.578
Why is that?
 

00:31:15.578 --> 00:31:19.492
Because he is still delivering
.2 down here when he makes the

00:31:19.492 --> 00:31:20.521
(.3,
.3) promise,

00:31:20.521 --> 00:31:23.809
but when he makes the (.3,
.3) promise he delivers more at

00:31:23.809 --> 00:31:26.625
the top,
namely .3, but that's the state

00:31:26.625 --> 00:31:28.740
he's sure is going to happen.
 

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:31.622
So compared to the (.2,
.2) promise he's giving away

00:31:31.622 --> 00:31:34.673
more money just in the state
that he thinks is going to

00:31:34.673 --> 00:31:35.240
occur.
 

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:36.509
That's very expensive for him.
 

00:31:36.509 --> 00:31:38.329
That's a horrible thing for him
to have to do.

00:31:38.329 --> 00:31:39.779
And who's lending him the money?
 

00:31:39.779 --> 00:31:42.763
It's the guy down here,
and the guy down here,

00:31:42.763 --> 00:31:44.288
that's the pessimist.
 

00:31:44.288 --> 00:31:48.154
He doesn't think that top
state's going to occur so he's

00:31:48.154 --> 00:31:51.808
only willing to pay extra money
at the beginning--

00:31:51.808 --> 00:31:53.921
he's not willing to pay very
much extra money at the

00:31:53.921 --> 00:31:56.489
beginning because he's going to
get stuff in a state he doesn't

00:31:56.489 --> 00:31:57.690
think is going to happen.
 

00:31:57.690 --> 00:31:59.798
So anyway, I don't have time
work it all out,

00:31:59.798 --> 00:32:04.250
but if you think it through
you'll realize that nobody wants

00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:07.800
to do this trade,
because the guys at the top who

00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:11.490
seem to have the greatest
advantage in borrowing more,

00:32:11.490 --> 00:32:13.970
when they borrow more in this
way where they're defaulting,

00:32:13.970 --> 00:32:16.270
they're actually paying more
only in the state that they

00:32:16.270 --> 00:32:18.740
think is going to occur and the
people doing the lending are

00:32:18.740 --> 00:32:21.210
getting money only in the state
they think won't occur.

00:32:21.210 --> 00:32:23.470
So both of them think it's a
worse arrangement than the

00:32:23.470 --> 00:32:25.200
original (.2,
.2) arrangement,

00:32:25.200 --> 00:32:29.044
and so even though there's a
price and it's available to be

00:32:29.044 --> 00:32:31.630
traded nobody will want to trade
it.

00:32:31.630 --> 00:32:35.262
So the market does indeed pick
