which is .75 divided by the

00:32:44.759 --> 00:32:50.868
cash down which is .55,
because you can borrow .2,

00:32:50.868 --> 00:32:54.058
and that's 1.4 or something.
 

00:32:54.058 --> 00:32:59.490
I don't know exactly,
but let's say 1.38 leverage,

00:32:59.490 --> 00:33:02.038
1.35 is the leverage.
 

00:33:02.038 --> 00:33:06.250
So it's not that high,
the leverage.

00:33:06.250 --> 00:33:08.821
And the principle is,
that we just discovered when

00:33:08.821 --> 00:33:10.868
you have this kind of
heterogeneity,

00:33:10.868 --> 00:33:12.892
different kinds of
heterogeneity produce different

00:33:12.892 --> 00:33:14.673
amount of leverage,
and I'm not going to be able to

00:33:14.673 --> 00:33:17.770
talk about that,
but with this kind of leverage

00:33:17.770 --> 00:33:22.868
the promise will always be the
maximum for which there is no

00:33:22.868 --> 00:33:23.818
default.
 

00:33:23.818 --> 00:33:25.663
That's how much borrowing is
going to happen,

00:33:25.663 --> 00:33:27.088
and the market's going to
allow.

00:33:27.088 --> 00:33:29.380
So in what market do we always
see that happening?

00:33:29.380 --> 00:33:32.578
In the Repo market,
it's a one day market

00:33:32.578 --> 00:33:33.538
overnight.
 

00:33:33.538 --> 00:33:36.323
You put up a security as
collateral, and you can borrow

00:33:36.323 --> 00:33:39.260
money on it, and there's almost
never any default on those

00:33:39.260 --> 00:33:39.880
markets.
 

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:43.451
Even in the tremendous crisis
we just had almost zero defaults

00:33:43.451 --> 00:33:44.740
in the Repo markets.
 

00:33:44.740 --> 00:33:46.529
Mortgage markets there were
defaults,

00:33:46.529 --> 00:33:49.186
but there the heterogeneity
isn't just how optimistic you

00:33:49.186 --> 00:33:50.452
are,
it's whether you like to live

00:33:50.452 --> 00:33:52.670
in the house or not,
so it's a different case which

00:33:52.670 --> 00:33:54.079
I won't have time to cover.
 

