00:35:48.889 --> 00:35:52.840
commonsensical thing in the
world, but remember it never got

00:35:52.840 --> 00:35:55.250
mentioned in this course,
right?

00:35:55.250 --> 00:35:57.000
It never gets mentioned in any
textbook.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.590
The price is supposed to be the
fundamental value,

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:02.510
the present value of all the
dividends,

00:36:02.510 --> 00:36:05.139
or the expected present value
of all the dividends,

00:36:05.139 --> 00:36:07.510
meaning minus the covariance or
something.

00:36:07.510 --> 00:36:09.789
Where was leverage in that
formula?

00:36:09.789 --> 00:36:13.150
It didn't happen because we
didn't have the idea.

00:36:13.150 --> 00:36:16.362
We assumed that everyone could
borrow as much as they wanted

00:36:16.362 --> 00:36:19.465
to, but here we see that they
can't borrow as much as they

00:36:19.465 --> 00:36:20.119
want to.
 

00:36:20.119 --> 00:36:21.789
They're limited in how much
they can borrow,

00:36:21.789 --> 00:36:24.550
and because they're limited
it's going to turn out,

00:36:24.550 --> 00:36:27.378
if you make the limit less
severe they're going to borrow

00:36:27.378 --> 00:36:29.550
more and the price is going to
be higher.

00:36:29.550 --> 00:36:31.838
So you ignore leverage by
saying people can always borrow

00:36:31.838 --> 00:36:34.947
whatever they want to,
then it never gets mentioned,

00:36:34.947 --> 00:36:37.469
but it's the heart of the
matter,

00:36:37.469 --> 00:36:40.679
I think, at least in a crisis.
 

00:36:40.679 --> 00:36:45.969
So let's just do one more
