wrong for things to collapse,

00:38:03.092 --> 00:38:06.570
but each time one of them goes
wrong you're a little closer to

00:38:06.570 --> 00:38:07.539
the collapse.
 

00:38:07.539 --> 00:38:14.958
So I make the assumption that
agents are all identical except

00:38:14.958 --> 00:38:17.605
agent H--
high H means you think you're

00:38:17.605 --> 00:38:19.802
going to get up moves,
but there are two moves,

00:38:19.802 --> 00:38:22.070
at the beginning and also in
the second period.

00:38:22.070 --> 00:38:24.713
So if you're an optimist about
the first up move you're also

00:38:24.713 --> 00:38:27.000
going to be an optimist about
the second up move.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.670
Now, let's suppose your H
equals .87, say,

00:38:29.670 --> 00:38:33.121
just to pick a number,
which it's going to turn out to

00:38:33.121 --> 00:38:34.489
be a pivotal guy.
 

00:38:34.489 --> 00:38:34.731
Mr.
 

00:38:34.731 --> 00:38:38.684
87 at the beginning,
the chances of going down are

00:38:38.684 --> 00:38:41.891
13 percent for him,
then 13 percent more,

00:38:41.891 --> 00:38:44.340
so the chance of getting a
disaster,

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:48.860
he thinks, is 13 percent
squared, 1.69 percent,

00:38:48.860 --> 00:38:50.179
under 2 percent.
 

00:38:50.179 --> 00:38:54.090
So he thinks the value of the
asset is over 98,

00:38:54.090 --> 00:38:58.291
under 2 percent here the rest
of the 98 must be over there

00:38:58.291 --> 00:39:02.554
somewhere,
so obviously his valuation is

00:39:02.554 --> 00:39:03.579
over 98.
 

00:39:03.579 --> 00:39:07.556
Now, once he gets down to here
he realizes the chances have

00:39:07.556 --> 00:39:10.230
gone from 1.69 percent to 13
percent.

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:14.280
So his valuation is going to be
a little bit more than 87,

00:39:14.280 --> 00:39:16.710
because it's going to be 87
percent of that and 13 percent

00:39:16.710 --> 00:39:19.250
of that,
so it's 87 plus a little bit.

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:21.972
So he's going to go down from
98 something,

00:39:21.972 --> 00:39:23.139
to 87 something.
 

00:39:23.139 --> 00:39:26.989
So of course when the first
down state happens everybody

00:39:26.989 --> 00:39:29.369
gets more pessimistic including
Mr.

00:39:29.369 --> 00:39:29.860
87.
 

00:39:29.860 --> 00:39:34.981
He now thinks that the asset
value maybe went from 98 to 87,

00:39:34.981 --> 00:39:39.927
which is an 11 point drop,
and everybody's going to have a

00:39:39.927 --> 00:39:40.710
drop.
 

00:39:40.710 --> 00:39:47.440
He went from 98 plus to 87 plus
a little bit.

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:51.820
So it's an 11 point drop is
what he thinks happened.

00:39:51.820 --> 00:39:53.789
So you can see this is bad news.
 

00:39:53.789 --> 00:39:57.170
When it takes two things to go
wrong the first piece of bad

00:39:57.170 --> 00:39:59.969
news people are going to take it
as bad news,

00:39:59.969 --> 00:40:03.545
but the interesting thing that
happens is that actually they

00:40:03.545 --> 00:40:04.820
get more uncertain.
 

00:40:04.820 --> 00:40:07.440
Things go up you get 1 for sure.
 

00:40:07.440 --> 00:40:09.280
Now you've learned something.
 

00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:10.090
There's no uncertainty.
 

00:40:10.090 --> 00:40:14.313
Here the move down created more
uncertainty than you had before,

00:40:14.313 --> 00:40:16.929
and not only that,
more disagreement.

00:40:16.929 --> 00:40:17.789
I mean, Mr.
 

00:40:17.789 --> 00:40:18.572
.9 and Mr.
 

00:40:18.572 --> 00:40:23.188
.8, neither of them thought
there was much chance of getting

00:40:23.188 --> 00:40:24.518
down to here.
 

00:40:24.518 --> 00:40:27.719
.9 thought 1 percent squared,
that's negligible.

00:40:27.719 --> 00:40:31.389
.8 thought 2 percent squared;
that's .004.

00:40:31.389 --> 00:40:34.025
The difference between
negligible an .004 is still

00:40:34.025 --> 00:40:35.652
negligible,
practically,

00:40:35.652 --> 00:40:39.186
so they hardly disagree here,
but once you get down to here

00:40:39.186 --> 00:40:41.474
they're both starting to get
more worried and they're

00:40:41.474 --> 00:40:44.159
actually differing a little bit
more than they did before.

00:40:44.159 --> 00:40:46.280
So that's what I think happens
in these crises.

00:40:46.280 --> 00:40:50.882
You go from everyone knowing if
25 things in a row go wrong

00:40:50.882 --> 00:40:54.173
we're in trouble,
but nobody's really thinking,

00:40:54.173 --> 00:40:56.349
except the guys at the very
bottom,

00:40:56.349 --> 00:40:58.920
that all of this stuff can go
wrong.

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:02.096
But once each thing goes wrong
now everyone gets more and more

00:41:02.096 --> 00:41:04.909
worried and there's more
separation between what people

00:41:04.909 --> 00:41:05.429
think.
 

00:41:05.429 --> 00:41:07.980
So that's just description of
the model.

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:12.400
So what's going to happen is
the question.

00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:16.893
So we're almost at the end here
because we don't have to do much

00:41:16.893 --> 00:41:18.320
more calculations.
 

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:22.527
So what will the prices be at
the beginning and down here,

00:41:22.527 --> 00:41:27.179
and what will the leverage be
at the beginning and down here?

00:41:27.179 --> 00:41:32.324
Well, remember our principle
that the leverage will always be

00:41:32.324 --> 00:41:37.041
worked out in this case of
heterogeneous beliefs so that

00:41:37.041 --> 00:41:40.210
people can promise--
so there will be no default.

00:41:40.210 --> 00:41:44.244
The maximum promise is the most
you can make without any chance

00:41:44.244 --> 00:41:45.090
of default.
 

00:41:45.090 --> 00:41:49.920
So you can see that--I'll tell
you what the prices are.

00:41:49.920 --> 00:41:51.639
They're going to be that.
 

00:41:51.639 --> 00:41:55.760
So if you made a two period
loan, a long loan,

00:41:55.760 --> 00:41:59.239
a lot can go wrong over a long
loan.

00:41:59.239 --> 00:42:01.860
You can get all the way down to
.2, so you're not going to be

00:42:01.860 --> 00:42:04.349
able to borrow very much if you
make a two period loan.

00:42:04.349 --> 00:42:08.110
If you make a one period loan,
in a day not much can go wrong.

00:42:08.110 --> 00:42:10.460
That's why these Repo markets
are so short.

00:42:10.460 --> 00:42:12.728
In one day practically nothing
can go wrong,

00:42:12.728 --> 00:42:15.949
well here something does go
wrong, but you can fall to .69.

00:42:15.949 --> 00:42:17.469
It's a lot better than .2.
 

00:42:17.469 --> 00:42:20.929
So you could borrow at the
beginning .69.

00:42:20.929 --> 00:42:23.523
That'll be the equilibrium
promise at the beginning,

00:42:23.523 --> 00:42:25.099
will be .69 with no interest.
 

00:42:25.099 --> 00:42:27.980
The equilibrium promise here
will be .2 with no interest.

00:42:27.980 --> 00:42:32.789
The equilibrium promise there
will be 1 with no interest.

00:42:32.789 --> 00:42:37.280
So this turns out to be the
equilibrium.

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:38.840
Why?
 

00:42:38.840 --> 00:42:40.980
Notice how shocking it is.
 

00:42:40.980 --> 00:42:45.940
Nobody thinks the price drop
from 95 to 69 is justified.

00:42:45.940 --> 00:42:48.170
That's a huge 26 percent drop.
 

00:42:48.170 --> 00:42:48.389
Mr.
 

00:42:48.389 --> 00:42:52.070
87, he thought the price should
go from 98 to 87.

00:42:52.070 --> 00:42:54.039
That's an 11 point drop.
 

00:42:54.039 --> 00:42:54.195
Mr.
 

00:42:54.195 --> 00:42:56.420
1 thought it was worth 1 at the
beginning.

00:42:56.420 --> 00:42:57.750
He still thinks it's worth 1.
 

00:42:57.750 --> 00:42:58.789
That's no drop.
 

00:42:58.789 --> 00:43:02.086
Mr. H equals 0 thought it was
worth .2 at the beginning and

00:43:02.086 --> 00:43:03.849
still thinks it's worth .2.
 

00:43:03.849 --> 00:43:05.210
That's no drop.
 

00:43:05.210 --> 00:43:09.869
No matter who you pick,
I think the worst one is .5,

00:43:09.869 --> 00:43:15.059
.5 thought it was worth--we
have to figure it out,

00:43:15.059 --> 00:43:17.579
25 percent chance of going down
here,

00:43:17.579 --> 00:43:18.829
75 up there.
 

00:43:18.829 --> 00:43:26.030
So .75 .5 is .8, right?
 

00:43:26.030 --> 00:43:31.949
25 percent of .2 is .05.
 

00:43:31.949 --> 00:43:35.722
So Mr. H equals .5,
thinks the expected payoff is

00:43:35.722 --> 00:43:40.125
.8,75 percent of one of those
1s, and 25 percent of .2 is

00:43:40.125 --> 00:43:41.539
another .05.
 

00:43:41.539 --> 00:43:43.768
So .75 and .05 is .8.
 

00:43:43.768 --> 00:43:47.800
So he thinks down here where
he's a .5 it's now worth .5 and

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:48.690
.5 of this.
 

00:43:48.690 --> 00:43:49.659
It's .6.
 

00:43:49.659 --> 00:43:52.152
So he thought the drop would be
from 80 to 60,

00:43:52.152 --> 00:43:53.150
a 20 point drop.
 

00:43:53.150 --> 00:43:55.936
That's the biggest drop anybody
could imagine,

00:43:55.936 --> 00:43:56.679
20 points.
 

00:43:56.679 --> 00:43:59.929
Most people are at 11 points or
0 points or something like that.

00:43:59.929 --> 00:44:02.559
Nobody's at a 26 point drop.
 

00:44:02.559 --> 00:44:06.539
That's way bigger than anybody
could imagine is justified by

00:44:06.539 --> 00:44:10.172
the bad news in the economy,
yet that's what the equilibrium

00:44:10.172 --> 00:44:14.050
becomes,
from 95 percent to 69 percent.

00:44:14.050 --> 00:44:15.429
So why is that?
 

00:44:15.429 --> 00:44:16.579
And that's the end of the story.
 

00:44:16.579 --> 00:44:18.030
What happened in the drop?
 

00:44:18.030 --> 00:44:22.460
Well, three things went wrong.
 

00:44:22.460 --> 00:44:25.826
The first thing is that 87 is
the marginal buyer,

00:44:25.826 --> 00:44:28.000
so everyone above him bought.
 

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:29.909
All these optimists were buying.
 

00:44:29.909 --> 00:44:32.820
Everyone else sold and lent
money.

00:44:32.820 --> 00:44:34.639
Student: You just assume
that, right.

00:44:34.639 --> 00:44:35.280
Prof: What?
 

00:44:35.280 --> 00:44:37.088
Student: You just said
let's assume 87 is the marginal

00:44:37.088 --> 00:44:37.329
buyer?
 

00:44:37.329 --> 00:44:39.592
Prof: I'm assuming that
and it's going to turn out to be

00:44:39.592 --> 00:44:40.360
the correct answer.
 

00:44:40.360 --> 00:44:42.010
Now, how did I know 87?
 

00:44:42.010 --> 00:44:43.929
Well, you'll see at the end.
 

00:44:43.929 --> 00:44:45.300
Yeah, question?
 

00:44:45.300 --> 00:44:45.768
No.
 

00:44:45.768 --> 00:44:50.920
Just fixing your hair,
that's okay.

00:44:50.920 --> 00:44:54.619
So Mr. 87 is the marginal buyer.
 

00:44:54.619 --> 00:44:56.309
So those guys at the top bought.
 

00:44:56.309 --> 00:44:58.530
Now, how could they afford to
buy so much?

00:44:58.530 --> 00:44:59.880
Well, they're borrowing so much.
 

00:44:59.880 --> 00:45:04.181
They're borrowing .69 plus they
already had their .31

00:45:04.181 --> 00:45:08.648
[correction: their .13],
so together they can spend .69

00:45:08.648 --> 00:45:09.309
.13.
 

00:45:09.309 --> 00:45:16.943
That's .82 that they're
spending and they're only buying

00:45:16.943 --> 00:45:21.940
87, and so 82 over 87 is about
95.

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:23.219
So there's a little rounding
going on.

00:45:23.219 --> 00:45:25.190
So that's why the price is .95.
 

00:45:25.190 --> 00:45:28.050
Now, why did it crash to .69?
 

00:45:28.050 --> 00:45:30.489
It crashed because look what
happened.

00:45:30.489 --> 00:45:34.864
These total optimists at the
beginning, the top 13 percent,

00:45:34.864 --> 00:45:39.465
they spent all the money that
they had, their 13 percent gold,

00:45:39.465 --> 00:45:41.730
they spent the 13 percent.
 

00:45:41.730 --> 00:45:45.070
They borrowed everything they
could to the hilt so they owed

00:45:45.070 --> 00:45:46.260
.69 in both states.
 

00:45:46.260 --> 00:45:47.860
So what happens to them here?
 

00:45:47.860 --> 00:45:50.554
They spent all their gold and
they owe the total value of

00:45:50.554 --> 00:45:51.469
their collateral.
 

00:45:51.469 --> 00:45:52.590
They're wiped out here.
 

00:45:52.590 --> 00:45:54.018
They've got nothing left.
 

00:45:54.018 --> 00:45:56.817
So the most optimistic people
in the economy,

00:45:56.817 --> 00:45:58.980
they're just out of the
economy.

00:45:58.980 --> 00:46:00.369
They've all gone bankrupt.
 

00:46:00.369 --> 00:46:04.925
So now we've got a smaller
population with less optimistic

00:46:04.925 --> 00:46:09.161
people, and so these new
optimists are going to do the

00:46:09.161 --> 00:46:10.360
buying now.
 

00:46:10.360 --> 00:46:13.070
Well, first of all they don't
think the asset's worth as much

00:46:13.070 --> 00:46:14.199
for a bunch of reasons.
 

00:46:14.199 --> 00:46:16.740
One is they got bad news,
so the people who are left

00:46:16.740 --> 00:46:19.929
don't think it's worth as much
as they did from the beginning.

00:46:19.929 --> 00:46:23.255
Plus the most optimistic people
at the beginning aren't there

00:46:23.255 --> 00:46:25.411
either,
and then lastly and most

00:46:25.411 --> 00:46:29.213
importantly the people who are
left can't borrow very much

00:46:29.213 --> 00:46:33.550
money because the leverage at
the beginning was .95 over .26,

00:46:33.550 --> 00:46:36.820
you could borrow 69,
so you had to pay down .26.

00:46:36.820 --> 00:46:38.650
That's 3.6 leverage.
 

00:46:38.650 --> 00:46:40.719
Here the price is .69.
 

00:46:40.719 --> 00:46:44.059
You can only borrow .2,
so you have to put .49 down.

00:46:44.059 --> 00:46:45.880
The leverage is 1.4.
 

00:46:45.880 --> 00:46:48.967
So you went from 3 and 1 half
leverage to 1 and 1 half

00:46:48.967 --> 00:46:49.610
leverage.
 

00:46:49.610 --> 00:46:53.568
The leverage collapsed,
and so these guys who are left

00:46:53.568 --> 00:46:57.753
they are not as optimistic
themselves because they've got

00:46:57.753 --> 00:47:00.891
bad news,
the most optimistic people are

00:47:00.891 --> 00:47:02.847
gone,
and the people who want to do

00:47:02.847 --> 00:47:04.518
the buying can't borrow as much.
 

00:47:04.518 --> 00:47:07.289
So there are three reasons that
drives the price down.

00:47:07.289 --> 00:47:10.320
The marginal buyer becomes a
much lower guy than before,

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:12.469
and so that's why the price is
lower.

00:47:12.469 --> 00:47:15.311
It's not just the bad news
because Mr.

00:47:15.311 --> 00:47:18.539
87 would never have justified
that drop.

00:47:18.539 --> 00:47:22.563
It's because the thing has
fallen into more pessimistic

00:47:22.563 --> 00:47:23.159
hands.
 

00:47:23.159 --> 00:47:26.447
So all those bankers and hedge
funds who bought all those

00:47:26.447 --> 00:47:29.679
mortgage securities at the
beginning, they've been wiped

00:47:29.679 --> 00:47:30.559
out by now.
 

00:47:30.559 --> 00:47:31.239
They're way up here.
 

00:47:31.239 --> 00:47:32.210
They can't buy.
 

00:47:32.210 --> 00:47:35.510
They're much more sober people
who are left who also know we've

00:47:35.510 --> 00:47:36.309
had bad news.
 

00:47:36.309 --> 00:47:38.996
They're willing to pay less to
begin with, and they are more

00:47:38.996 --> 00:47:41.000
pessimistic, and they can't
borrow very much,

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:43.050
so the price drops for all
those reasons.

00:47:43.050 --> 00:47:45.480
I think that's the essence of
the crash.

00:47:45.480 --> 00:47:48.188
Three reasons,
the people going bankrupt who

00:47:48.188 --> 00:47:51.969
are the most optimistic buyers,
the second reason because the

00:47:51.969 --> 00:47:53.039
news was bad.
 

00:47:53.039 --> 00:47:53.940
That's the first reason.
 

00:47:53.940 --> 00:47:57.793
The news was bad,
optimistic buyers going out and

00:47:57.793 --> 00:48:02.369
the leverage collapsing,
so the price drops a long way.

00:48:02.369 --> 00:48:04.760
So I'll end with one more slide
and then sum up.

00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:09.050
The last slide is his question
about the classes of people.

00:48:09.050 --> 00:48:12.789
It's a little different now
than it was before.

00:48:12.789 --> 00:48:14.710
There are different classes of
people.

00:48:14.710 --> 00:48:16.360
So let's just think about this.
 

00:48:16.360 --> 00:48:20.461
Why was the marginal buyer Mr.
 

00:48:20.461 --> 00:48:21.010
87?
 

00:48:21.010 --> 00:48:23.882
I mean, after all we just
computed, Mr.

00:48:23.882 --> 00:48:27.510
87 thinks the value of the
asset's 98, not 95.

00:48:27.510 --> 00:48:27.840
Mr.
 

00:48:27.840 --> 00:48:33.235
86 also thinks the value of the
asset is 98 about,

00:48:33.235 --> 00:48:35.880
so why didn't 86 buy?
 

00:48:35.880 --> 00:48:37.710
He was getting a good deal at
the beginning.

00:48:37.710 --> 00:48:41.650
Why wasn't 86 buying when he
thinks it's worth 98 here?

00:48:41.650 --> 00:48:41.885
Mr.
 

00:48:41.885 --> 00:48:44.949
.86, remember,
is not supposed to buy.

00:48:44.949 --> 00:48:48.889
He's going to buy the next time.
 

00:48:48.889 --> 00:48:49.556
See Mr.
 

00:48:49.556 --> 00:48:53.179
86 there, he's the cautious
optimist.

00:48:53.179 --> 00:48:53.384
Mr.
 

00:48:53.384 --> 00:48:56.860
86 there, just below 87,
he's going to buy after the

00:48:56.860 --> 00:48:59.179
crash, but he's not buying now.
 

00:48:59.179 --> 00:49:07.750
So why is it that he's not
buying at the beginning?

00:49:07.750 --> 00:49:11.521
Well, so this is the only
subtlety, but it's the answer to

00:49:11.521 --> 00:49:12.579
your question.
 

00:49:12.579 --> 00:49:12.809
Mr.
 

00:49:12.809 --> 00:49:16.409
86 says to himself,
"I can make a profit.

00:49:16.409 --> 00:49:20.349
I think it's worth 98 and I
only have to pay 95.

00:49:20.349 --> 00:49:22.820
That's like a 3 percent
expected return and I'm risk

00:49:22.820 --> 00:49:24.079
neutral so that's great.
 

00:49:24.079 --> 00:49:26.550
If I'm right it goes from 95 to
100.

00:49:26.550 --> 00:49:27.949
I can get 5 percent.
 

00:49:27.949 --> 00:49:30.318
On the other hand,
maybe I should wait for the

00:49:30.318 --> 00:49:30.739
crash.
 

00:49:30.739 --> 00:49:34.039
If the crash comes I only have
to pay 69.

00:49:34.039 --> 00:49:38.420
I can get 40 percent return,
31 over 69, whatever that is.

00:49:38.420 --> 00:49:42.670
I can get a 40 percent return
if there's a crash.

00:49:42.670 --> 00:49:48.449
That's much better than my 5
percent if I'm right."

00:49:48.449 --> 00:49:53.699
So that guy is waiting to make
money in the cash.

00:49:53.699 --> 00:49:56.992
So of course by waiting and
buying in the crash he's helping

00:49:56.992 --> 00:50:00.119
to reduce the terrible calamity,
because he's a buyer.

00:50:00.119 --> 00:50:03.748
If we just had more people like
that--I think of that as Warren

00:50:03.748 --> 00:50:06.266
Buffett, I called him the
cautious optimist,

00:50:06.266 --> 00:50:07.612
all the way down to Mr.
 

00:50:07.612 --> 00:50:08.139
.74.
 

00:50:08.139 --> 00:50:08.336
Mr.
 

00:50:08.336 --> 00:50:11.427
.75, for example,
also thinks the asset is worth

00:50:11.427 --> 00:50:15.240
more than .95 at the beginning,
but he doesn't buy either,

00:50:15.240 --> 00:50:17.753
so all these people,
the cautious optimists,

00:50:17.753 --> 00:50:20.706
they're holding out for the
crash and the crash would be

00:50:20.706 --> 00:50:23.481
much worse without them,
but they don't eliminate the

00:50:23.481 --> 00:50:25.480
crash because there are not
enough of them.

00:50:25.480 --> 00:50:27.675
So here are the three classes
of people you were thinking

00:50:27.675 --> 00:50:27.989
about.
 

00:50:27.989 --> 00:50:29.420
They're not quite as optimistic.
 

00:50:29.420 --> 00:50:33.449
They still think it's a good
buy, but they decide not to buy

00:50:33.449 --> 00:50:35.090
waiting for the crash.
 

00:50:35.090 --> 00:50:38.199
Now, how did I know that it
would stop at 87 and 74?

00:50:38.199 --> 00:50:39.268
How did I get all those numbers?
 

00:50:39.268 --> 00:50:41.985
Well, I don't have time to
derive them, those are the

00:50:41.985 --> 00:50:44.389
equations, but I can explain it
very simply.

00:50:44.389 --> 00:50:47.436
You see, thinking you're going
to take advantage of the crash

00:50:47.436 --> 00:50:49.010
means you must have a high H.
 

00:50:49.010 --> 00:50:51.293
You think if things go here
they're still going to end up

00:50:51.293 --> 00:50:51.579
okay.
 

00:50:51.579 --> 00:50:53.849
That's why you think there's a
big profit opportunity.

00:50:53.849 --> 00:50:56.914
But if your H is too high you
don't think you're ever going to

00:50:56.914 --> 00:50:57.869
get to the crash.
 

00:50:57.869 --> 00:51:00.900
So you've only got this small
intermediate group of people,

00:51:00.900 --> 00:51:04.106
the Warren Buffett like people,
who are optimistic enough to

00:51:04.106 --> 00:51:07.150
think that we're going to pull
out of our depression,

00:51:07.150 --> 00:51:10.969
pull out of the crash and still
there's a profit opportunity,

00:51:10.969 --> 00:51:14.909
and yet think that the crash is
likely enough so that they'll

00:51:14.909 --> 00:51:15.829
wait for it.
 

00:51:15.829 --> 00:51:17.927
People who think they'll make a
bigger profit,

00:51:17.927 --> 00:51:20.818
higher H once the crash starts,
well, they don't even think the

00:51:20.818 --> 00:51:22.170
crash is going to happen.
 

00:51:22.170 --> 00:51:26.175
So I've made a big assumption
that the people with high Hs

00:51:26.175 --> 00:51:29.480
always have high Hs,
but I think that's life.

00:51:29.480 --> 00:51:31.650
I think that's not a bad
assumption.

00:51:31.650 --> 00:51:34.771
Every hedge fund guy I've ever
talked to who thought that this

00:51:34.771 --> 00:51:37.894
was a low probability event also
thought we were going to come

00:51:37.894 --> 00:51:40.250
out of it and things wouldn't be
that bad.

00:51:40.250 --> 00:51:43.179
So I'm not saying that these
people don't learn.

00:51:43.179 --> 00:51:44.130
Everybody learns.
 

00:51:44.130 --> 00:51:46.210
When they see the first piece
of bad news they're more

00:51:46.210 --> 00:51:46.760
pessimistic.
 

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:51.119
You go from 1.69 percent to 13
percent.

00:51:51.119 --> 00:51:52.570
So it's not like people aren't
learning.

00:51:52.570 --> 00:51:55.168
They are learning,
but relative to the rest of the

00:51:55.168 --> 00:51:58.349
population if you started
optimistic you stay optimistic,

00:51:58.349 --> 00:52:01.278
and that's why there's only a
small group of Warren Buffetts

00:52:01.278 --> 00:52:02.719
who can save the situation.
 

00:52:02.719 --> 00:52:06.608
So that's my model of the
leverage cycle,

00:52:06.608 --> 00:52:08.360
of what happens.
 

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:11.795
Three bad things happen,
bad news, can't do anything

00:52:11.795 --> 00:52:16.039
about that, the leveraged buyers
get crushed, go out of business

00:52:16.039 --> 00:52:17.860
and leverage collapses.
 

00:52:17.860 --> 00:52:20.637
And when the prices are really
low the whole economy is

00:52:20.637 --> 00:52:23.570
suffering tremendously and
innocent people who had nothing

00:52:23.570 --> 00:52:26.456
to do with all these markets,
the price of everything,

00:52:26.456 --> 00:52:28.400
every asset is low so they
can't borrow.

00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:29.309
They can't get loans.
 

00:52:29.309 --> 00:52:30.989
Margins are so tough.
 

00:52:30.989 --> 00:52:31.730
They're small businesses.
 

00:52:31.730 --> 00:52:32.449
They can't borrow.
 

00:52:32.449 --> 00:52:36.467
They're totally crushed down
here, so how would we save the

00:52:36.467 --> 00:52:37.159
economy?
 

00:52:37.159 --> 00:52:40.510
We'd undo the three things that
happened.

00:52:40.510 --> 00:52:43.913
We can't undo the bad news,
but the three things that

00:52:43.913 --> 00:52:46.268
happened were uncertainty went
up.

00:52:46.268 --> 00:52:48.869
It wasn't just bad news,
it was scary bad news.

00:52:48.869 --> 00:52:53.179
So this gap between 1 and .2 is
much bigger than that gap.

00:52:53.179 --> 00:52:54.869
That's why the leverage went
down.

00:52:54.869 --> 00:52:56.320
Volatility went up.
 

00:52:56.320 --> 00:52:59.150
So you have to contain the bad
news.

00:52:59.150 --> 00:53:00.670
That would help.
 

00:53:00.670 --> 00:53:03.090
You have to contain the bad
news, that's A.

00:53:03.090 --> 00:53:06.226
So you can't eliminate the bad
news, but you can contain the

00:53:06.226 --> 00:53:07.768
volatility of the bad news.
 

00:53:07.768 --> 00:53:09.905
Secondly you have to increase
the leverage,

00:53:09.905 --> 00:53:12.907
and thirdly you have to make up
for the people who've gotten

00:53:12.907 --> 00:53:13.619
destroyed.
 

00:53:13.619 --> 00:53:15.719
The buying power is gone.
 

00:53:15.719 --> 00:53:18.550
Somehow the government has to
replace that temporarily.

00:53:18.550 --> 00:53:21.141
So those are the three things
we should be doing now,

00:53:21.141 --> 00:53:24.081
and in the long run we should
never have let leverage get so

00:53:24.081 --> 00:53:24.929
high up here.
 

00:53:24.929 --> 00:53:26.626
That's what made the price so
high up here,

00:53:26.626 --> 00:53:29.009
and that's why everyone got
wiped out down here because they

00:53:29.009 --> 00:53:30.099
were borrowing so much.
 

00:53:30.099 --> 00:53:31.630
We should never have let that
happen.

00:53:31.630 --> 00:53:35.275
So if we regulate the economy
not to let leverage get so high

00:53:35.275 --> 00:53:38.389
we won't have such a crash,
but if we do have a crash the

00:53:38.389 --> 00:53:40.878
way to deal with it is to undo
the three things that went

00:53:40.878 --> 00:53:41.280
wrong.
 

00:53:41.280 --> 00:53:44.380
That's the sort of story that
I've been telling.

00:53:44.380 --> 00:53:45.059
Yes?
 

00:53:45.059 --> 00:53:47.240
Student: Do you have a
theory for what the right amount

00:53:47.240 --> 00:53:47.849
of leverage is?
 

00:53:47.849 --> 00:53:51.880
Prof: That's a wonderful
question, and of course I've

00:53:51.880 --> 00:53:53.590
been asked that before.
 

00:53:53.590 --> 00:53:56.530
So let me put it in several
different ways.

00:53:56.530 --> 00:53:59.050
Let's take the most
hypercritical way.

00:53:59.050 --> 00:54:03.103
I presented this theory,
remember, starting in 2000,

00:54:03.103 --> 00:54:05.170
so way before the crash.
 

00:54:05.170 --> 00:54:07.500
And so people would say then,
"Oh,

00:54:07.500 --> 00:54:09.958
very nice, very cute,
but first all there's not going

00:54:09.958 --> 00:54:12.655
to be a crash and secondly how
could we ever know what the

00:54:12.655 --> 00:54:14.170
right amount of leverage is.
 

00:54:14.170 --> 00:54:18.289
It's an impossible pie in the
sky goal to regulate leverage.

00:54:18.289 --> 00:54:21.135
Well, you see,
that's why--I say it's

00:54:21.135 --> 00:54:24.851
difficult, I agree,
but we've already faced this

00:54:24.851 --> 00:54:25.800
problem.
 

00:54:25.800 --> 00:54:27.099
We regulate the interest rate.
 

00:54:27.099 --> 00:54:30.108
How does the Fed know that the
interest rate's too low or too

00:54:30.108 --> 00:54:30.460
high?
 

00:54:30.460 --> 00:54:33.246
What the Fed does is it
monitors a bunch of stuff and

00:54:33.246 --> 00:54:35.230
realizes the economy is
overheated.

00:54:35.230 --> 00:54:36.480
Things are changing.
 

00:54:36.480 --> 00:54:41.115
Suddenly output is going way up
and inflation is starting to go

00:54:41.115 --> 00:54:41.489
up.
 

00:54:41.489 --> 00:54:43.132
Then the Fed raises the
interest rate,

00:54:43.132 --> 00:54:45.621
or maybe people are being
thrown out of work then the Fed

00:54:45.621 --> 00:54:46.909
lowers the interest rate.
 

00:54:46.909 --> 00:54:48.960
So something changes in the
economy.

00:54:48.960 --> 00:54:52.070
They don't know so precisely
what to do,

00:54:52.070 --> 00:54:54.755
but something's changed that
gives them a clue about which

00:54:54.755 --> 00:54:57.704
way to move interest rates,
and over the course of 80

00:54:57.704 --> 00:55:00.039
years, I guess since the
Depression,

00:55:00.039 --> 00:55:03.163
since it was created,
over 70 or 80 years since then

00:55:03.163 --> 00:55:06.960
they've gotten better and better
at regulating the interest.

00:55:06.960 --> 00:55:13.429
So I put this picture up for a
reason last class.

00:55:13.429 --> 00:55:17.757
You remember the picture,
which I'm going to get to now,

00:55:17.757 --> 00:55:20.039
of the history of leverage.
 

00:55:20.039 --> 00:55:22.713
So here's the history of
leverage, the purple,

00:55:22.713 --> 00:55:24.139
in the housing market.
 

00:55:24.139 --> 00:55:27.681
And then the blue is the
history of leverage,

00:55:27.681 --> 00:55:30.579
it's the loan to value,
basically.

00:55:30.579 --> 00:55:34.920
I put money down starting from
the top and going down.

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:37.159
So from the bottom it's loan to
value.

00:55:37.159 --> 00:55:41.253
So I've got the history of loan
to value in the securities

00:55:41.253 --> 00:55:43.840
market and in the mortgage
market.

00:55:43.840 --> 00:55:46.351
Now, I think that the Fed
should be monitoring this,

00:55:46.351 --> 00:55:48.123
and not only should be
monitoring it,

00:55:48.123 --> 00:55:51.079
should be making it as public
as the interest rates are.

00:55:51.079 --> 00:55:55.222
So how come I had to present
Ellington's data on observations

00:55:55.222 --> 00:55:59.130
it made in the market,
because Ellington seems to have

00:55:59.130 --> 00:56:03.139
been the only company in the
county that kept this data.

00:56:03.139 --> 00:56:05.536
Nobody else seemed to recognize
how important it was,

00:56:05.536 --> 00:56:06.320
and we kept it.
 

00:56:06.320 --> 00:56:09.559
So the Fed doesn't have these
numbers going back.

00:56:09.559 --> 00:56:12.768
If it did it would have seen
that leverage had suddenly

00:56:12.768 --> 00:56:16.275
jumped up here and that leverage
was much higher than it was

00:56:16.275 --> 00:56:18.077
before,
and it would see if it

00:56:18.077 --> 00:56:20.898
monitored leverage in the
housing market that leverage was

00:56:20.898 --> 00:56:21.690
skyrocketing.
 

00:56:21.690 --> 00:56:23.670
Of course everybody knew this,
they just didn't think it was

00:56:23.670 --> 00:56:25.079
an important thing to pay
attention to,

00:56:25.079 --> 00:56:27.206
but if they were paying
attention to it and keeping

00:56:27.206 --> 00:56:29.242
these numbers,
we had to do this at Ellington

00:56:29.242 --> 00:56:31.958
by going house by house through
every house looking at what the

00:56:31.958 --> 00:56:33.710
leverage was and taking the
average,

00:56:33.710 --> 00:56:35.753
if they had done that,
I mean they could have done

00:56:35.753 --> 00:56:38.054
that easily,
and if they did do that,

00:56:38.054 --> 00:56:41.951
and if they were publishing it,
and every economist was aware

00:56:41.951 --> 00:56:44.860
of it I think things would have
been very different.

00:56:44.860 --> 00:56:49.130
They would have said we ought
to tighten leverage.

00:56:49.130 --> 00:56:51.230
Exactly how much should we
tighten it?

00:56:51.230 --> 00:56:53.987
Well, they would have said,
"I don't know exactly,

00:56:53.987 --> 00:56:56.795
but we would have forced banks
not to allow loans with 3

00:56:56.795 --> 00:56:57.969
percent down."
 

00:56:57.969 --> 00:57:00.436
Should it be 10 percent,
or 15 percent,

00:57:00.436 --> 00:57:01.409
or 8 percent?
 

00:57:01.409 --> 00:57:03.820
It's a little hard to say what
exactly the right number is,

00:57:03.820 --> 00:57:06.974
but we would have picked a
number higher than 3 percent and

00:57:06.974 --> 00:57:09.150
we would have avoided a huge
problem,

00:57:09.150 --> 00:57:12.405
and in later years we'll get
better and better at picking

00:57:12.405 --> 00:57:13.219
that number.
 

00:57:13.219 --> 00:57:17.059
So I'm trying to answer your
question.

00:57:17.059 --> 00:57:19.840
So in the securities market
another thing you could do,

00:57:19.840 --> 00:57:23.829
another trick you could do is
you could say we'll pass a rule

00:57:23.829 --> 00:57:26.576
that says you can't--
here leverage is going down,

00:57:26.576 --> 00:57:26.880
right?
 

00:57:26.880 --> 00:57:28.820
They're asking for more and
more margins.

00:57:28.820 --> 00:57:34.045
You could pass a rule that says
you can't double your margins

00:57:34.045 --> 00:57:37.880
from 10 percent to 20 percent or
20 to 40.

00:57:37.880 --> 00:57:42.092
You can't double them in under
four months, say,

00:57:42.092 --> 00:57:45.679
on average across some security
class.

00:57:45.679 --> 00:57:49.731
You can't double them in less
than four months or less than

00:57:49.731 --> 00:57:50.639
six months.
 

00:57:50.639 --> 00:57:54.768
So that would have kept
leverage from collapsing so

00:57:54.768 --> 00:57:57.159
fast,
and then lenders knowing that

00:57:57.159 --> 00:58:00.237
when the crisis was starting,
you know, they're making one

00:58:00.237 --> 00:58:00.719
day loans.
 

00:58:00.719 --> 00:58:01.619
See, they always think.
 

00:58:01.619 --> 00:58:04.577
"Well, it's a one day loan
and things start to look dicey

00:58:04.577 --> 00:58:07.389
I'll just demand a huge amount
of leverage the next day.

00:58:07.389 --> 00:58:09.695
I'll get my money back tomorrow
and then the day after tomorrow

00:58:09.695 --> 00:58:11.110
I'm not going to make the same
loan.

00:58:11.110 --> 00:58:12.820
I'll ask for a lot more
margin."

00:58:12.820 --> 00:58:14.623
So I'm saying,
suppose you tell them in

00:58:14.623 --> 00:58:17.375
advance you have to keep making
the same loan and you can't

00:58:17.375 --> 00:58:18.420
double the margin?
 

00:58:18.420 --> 00:58:20.748
You can increase it but you
have to take at least six months

00:58:20.748 --> 00:58:21.340
to double it.
 

00:58:21.340 --> 00:58:24.206
Well, they'll know in advance
that they're not going to be

00:58:24.206 --> 00:58:26.320
able to react very quickly to
problems,

00:58:26.320 --> 00:58:29.407
and so in advance they'll ask
for more margin down so they

00:58:29.407 --> 00:58:32.873
won't have to double to get to a
safe level when something starts

00:58:32.873 --> 00:58:35.420
happening because they'll
already be safer.

00:58:35.420 --> 00:58:38.760
So that's a way of not having
to actually know what the right

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:42.047
number is by just slowing down
their response and relying on

00:58:42.047 --> 00:58:44.998
them to anticipate how bad
things might be and they're

00:58:44.998 --> 00:58:47.840
already starting to respond at
the beginning.

00:58:47.840 --> 00:58:50.429
So I'm not saying I've got
exactly the right formula,

00:58:50.429 --> 00:58:52.775
but you see I think if you
think about it and start to work

00:58:52.775 --> 00:58:54.434
on this,
and most importantly you make

00:58:54.434 --> 00:58:56.813
these numbers public,
you're going to change the way

00:58:56.813 --> 00:59:00.179
everybody,
you know, rules will develop.

00:59:00.179 --> 00:59:02.018
Yeah?
 

00:59:02.018 --> 00:59:04.072
Student: To sort of
connect to that,

00:59:04.072 --> 00:59:07.052
so are they going to set like
one leverage rate or is it going

00:59:07.052 --> 00:59:08.518
to be like for each class?
 

00:59:08.518 --> 00:59:10.335
Prof: Yes,
each class of security will

00:59:10.335 --> 00:59:11.489
have a different leverage.
 

00:59:11.489 --> 00:59:14.663
Student: When you say
class of security like do you

00:59:14.663 --> 00:59:16.000
mean like different...
 

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:21.150
Prof: Well,
the government already makes a

00:59:21.150 --> 00:59:22.820
lot of loans through Fannie Mae
and Freddie Mac,

00:59:22.820 --> 00:59:25.670
but Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac
will have to ask for at least 20

00:59:25.670 --> 00:59:26.360
percent down.
 

00:59:26.360 --> 00:59:28.800
Prime securities,
prime mortgages will have to

00:59:28.800 --> 00:59:31.349
have at least this much amount
of money down.

00:59:31.349 --> 00:59:33.614
So, on the housing market
you'll have to have a certain

00:59:33.614 --> 00:59:34.579
amount of money down.
 

00:59:34.579 --> 00:59:38.280
On Treasuries you can have a
very high leverage.

00:59:38.280 --> 00:59:41.119
On mortgages,
plain simple mortgages,

00:59:41.119 --> 00:59:45.773
you can have not quite as high
a leverage, but a pretty high

00:59:45.773 --> 00:59:46.800
leverage.
 

00:59:46.800 --> 00:59:48.949
On mortgage derivatives,
which are much more

00:59:48.949 --> 00:59:51.349
complicated, the leverage has to
be much less.

00:59:51.349 --> 00:59:54.590
So you might say there'll be
some rule that says--

00:59:54.590 --> 00:59:59.780
so anyway those are the kinds
of classes that I have in mind,

00:59:59.780 --> 01:00:03.510
and we have to work out exactly
how they're going to be

01:00:03.510 --> 01:00:04.340
regulated.
 

01:00:04.340 --> 01:00:05.630
So it's a little bit
complicated.

01:00:05.630 --> 01:00:07.090
So let me answer your question
in two parts.

01:00:07.090 --> 01:00:09.820
Yes, it has to depend on the
kind of security,

01:00:09.820 --> 01:00:13.034
and b) even trying to answer
your question I'm revealing that

01:00:13.034 --> 01:00:16.679
it's not so obvious exactly what
the formula is and how to do it,

01:00:16.679 --> 01:00:18.429
but this has to be worked out.
 

01:00:18.429 --> 01:00:19.230
Yep?
 

01:00:19.230 --> 01:00:22.106
Student: Is this some
kind of like Phillips curve

01:00:22.106 --> 01:00:25.141
relationship here that you could
make between the amount of

01:00:25.141 --> 01:00:28.280
leverage and unemployment that
kind of it's all the same like

01:00:28.280 --> 01:00:31.000
Phillips curve like other
occasions that end up being

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:32.570
awful also or is it...
 

01:00:32.570 --> 01:00:33.289
Prof: Yes, yes.
 

01:00:33.289 --> 01:00:36.773
I think that's the whole point
of the crisis that the things

01:00:36.773 --> 01:00:38.250
feedback on each other.
 

01:00:38.250 --> 01:00:40.090
The feedback is the most
important thing.

01:00:40.090 --> 01:00:43.469
So in the crisis let's take any
one of these.

01:00:43.469 --> 01:00:48.001
When leverage starts to go down
that makes the prices start to

01:00:48.001 --> 01:00:50.007
go down,
but when the prices start to go

01:00:50.007 --> 01:00:52.309
down people get more worried
that things are going to go down

01:00:52.309 --> 01:00:53.646
further,
I mean, they have good reason

01:00:53.646 --> 01:00:55.264
to worry,
and so the leverage goes down

01:00:55.264 --> 01:00:57.170
more which makes the prices go
down more,

01:00:57.170 --> 01:00:59.018
and so they feed back on each
other.

01:00:59.018 --> 01:01:04.679
So definitely it's a spiral of
one thing affecting the other.

01:01:04.679 --> 01:01:06.739
And of course,
the more the prices are going

01:01:06.739 --> 01:01:09.471
down the more the optimists are
losing money and your best

01:01:09.471 --> 01:01:12.018
buyers are getting wiped out,
and that's a third thing.

01:01:12.018 --> 01:01:15.159
Those three things are always
feeding back on each other.

01:01:15.159 --> 01:01:16.780
Student: Is there a
Lucas like critique,

01:01:16.780 --> 01:01:19.523
though, of saying that people
should be able to expect this

01:01:19.523 --> 01:01:21.889
coming forward and they should
account for that?

01:01:21.889 --> 01:01:23.472
Prof: No,
because the model was totally

01:01:23.472 --> 01:01:23.860
rational.
 

01:01:23.860 --> 01:01:25.869
Every person did expect all
this.

01:01:25.869 --> 01:01:28.650
Everyone anticipated perfectly
what would happen.

01:01:28.650 --> 01:01:35.594
So Lucas critique is people
should realize the environment

01:01:35.594 --> 01:01:39.159
they're in,
but here in this environment

01:01:39.159 --> 01:01:43.148
everybody up here understood
from the very beginning that the

01:01:43.148 --> 01:01:45.739
prices were going to go down to
.69.

01:01:45.739 --> 01:01:49.623
They realized that there was
going to be this acceleration of

01:01:49.623 --> 01:01:51.728
problems,
and so they all anticipated it,

01:01:51.728 --> 01:01:54.217
but still they wanted to buy
because they didn't think they

01:01:54.217 --> 01:01:55.590
were going to get down there.
 

01:01:55.590 --> 01:01:57.360
They thought they were going to
go up here.

01:01:57.360 --> 01:02:02.264
So remember,
I don't know if I have it in

01:02:02.264 --> 01:02:09.865
this slide, but one of my most
amazing pictures was this one of

01:02:09.865 --> 01:02:13.789
what happened to the market.
 

01:02:13.789 --> 01:02:14.820
Open.
 

01:02:14.820 --> 01:02:17.797
So what happened to the market
here, which I think I showed you

01:02:17.797 --> 01:02:19.286
last time, I mean,
I know I did,

01:02:19.286 --> 01:02:21.159
but I'll just show it to you
again.

01:02:21.159 --> 01:02:24.170
Now with this new perspective
you can look at it.

01:02:24.170 --> 01:02:36.268
Presents, so this is Jerusalem,
I gave this talk in Jerusalem.

01:02:36.268 --> 01:02:48.960
Second talk,
so you remember this picture?

01:02:48.960 --> 01:02:50.530
I hope it was in this slide.
 

01:02:50.530 --> 01:02:52.059
Yes, it was here.
 

01:02:52.059 --> 01:02:52.639
Here.
 

01:02:52.639 --> 01:02:54.489
Remember what happened in the
world?

01:02:54.489 --> 01:02:58.070
It was shocking how bad and how
fast it was.

01:02:58.070 --> 01:03:04.760
So in 2007, beginning of 2007,
right, we're not far from the

01:03:04.760 --> 01:03:07.030
beginning of 2007.
 

01:03:07.030 --> 01:03:11.452
That's three years ago people
were expecting 40 percent losses

01:03:11.452 --> 01:03:13.409
for these lower tranches.
 

01:03:13.409 --> 01:03:16.530
So how could you get such an
astronomical loss?

01:03:16.530 --> 01:03:17.840
What was happening?
 

01:03:17.840 --> 01:03:21.018
They were already anticipating
this spiral.

01:03:21.018 --> 01:03:24.039
If you looked at just what
housing prices were there,

01:03:24.039 --> 01:03:27.090
and you say 30 percent guys
being thrown out,

01:03:27.090 --> 01:03:29.639
and housing prices are down 4
percent,

01:03:29.639 --> 01:03:32.507
that's hardly any loss at all,
because if you get 96 percent

01:03:32.507 --> 01:03:35.617
back on the house and you have a
few expenses and only 30 percent

01:03:35.617 --> 01:03:38.510
are defaulting,
there was hardly anybody

01:03:38.510 --> 01:03:39.469
defaulting.
 

01:03:39.469 --> 01:03:42.041
Remember that curve we showed
where there weren't almost any

01:03:42.041 --> 01:03:43.829
losses and no one going
delinquent yet?

01:03:43.829 --> 01:03:46.266
They already anticipated that
there were going to be lots of

01:03:46.266 --> 01:03:48.621
people thrown out of their
houses and when they got thrown

01:03:48.621 --> 01:03:51.349
out of their houses the housing
prices were going to collapse.

01:03:51.349 --> 01:03:54.331
So this market was collapsing
already because people were

01:03:54.331 --> 01:03:57.204
anticipating a lot of the
feedbacks and stuff that were

01:03:57.204 --> 01:03:58.590
going to happen later.
 

01:03:58.590 --> 01:04:01.143
They didn't just extrapolate
the number of defaults,

01:04:01.143 --> 01:04:03.947
they also had to extrapolate
the housing prices and stuff

01:04:03.947 --> 01:04:04.699
going down.
 

01:04:04.699 --> 01:04:11.675
And so in this model everybody
is doing that complicated

01:04:11.675 --> 01:04:17.889
extrapolation and they're
figuring it all out,

01:04:17.889 --> 01:04:20.382
but even so they still want to
put themselves in the cycle

01:04:20.382 --> 01:04:22.920
because they still think they
have a profit opportunity.

01:04:22.920 --> 01:04:24.929
They can't stop themselves from
investing.

01:04:24.929 --> 01:04:26.530
That's why you need regulation.
 

01:04:26.530 --> 01:04:27.710
It's like a prisoner's dilemma.
 

01:04:27.710 --> 01:04:29.219
Everybody knows what the danger
is,

01:04:29.219 --> 01:04:32.036
they still want to do it and
the only way to stop them from

01:04:32.036 --> 01:04:33.943
doing it,
you can't lecture them about

01:04:33.943 --> 01:04:36.184
irrational exuberance,
they know what's going to

01:04:36.184 --> 01:04:37.820
happen and they still want to do
it.

01:04:37.820 --> 01:04:39.690
They don't think that's going
to happen.

01:04:39.690 --> 01:04:41.730
They know what could happen and
they still want to do it.

01:04:41.730 --> 01:04:45.989
Now, I think in reality Shiller
is partly right.

01:04:45.989 --> 01:04:48.782
I think that people didn't
really realize how bad it could

01:04:48.782 --> 01:04:49.469
have gotten.
 

01:04:49.469 --> 01:04:51.170
My own hedge fund lost money.
 

01:04:51.170 --> 01:04:54.313
We didn't anticipate how bad it
was because so many things went

01:04:54.313 --> 01:04:54.719
wrong.
 

01:04:54.719 --> 01:04:57.090
We just underestimated all the
feedbacks.

01:04:57.090 --> 01:04:59.813
So there is the spiral and
there were just more things

01:04:59.813 --> 01:05:01.559
going wrong than we anticipated.
 

01:05:01.559 --> 01:05:04.050
So I wouldn't stick 100 percent
to my story.

01:05:04.050 --> 01:05:06.913
I think there's something to
what Shiller says,

01:05:06.913 --> 01:05:10.710
but I wouldn't definitely stick
to 100 percent of his story of

01:05:10.710 --> 01:05:13.139
it being all irrational
exuberance.

01:05:13.139 --> 01:05:15.250
Any other questions?
 

01:05:15.250 --> 01:05:19.492
Now that we have five minutes
left for--so I'm willing to keep

01:05:19.492 --> 01:05:20.050
going.
 

01:05:20.050 --> 01:05:21.929
So let's just pause.
 

01:05:21.929 --> 01:05:25.617
Any more questions on this
story of the crisis or anything

01:05:25.617 --> 01:05:28.659
else about the crisis you want
to ask, or...?

01:05:28.659 --> 01:05:29.340
Yeah?
 

01:05:29.340 --> 01:05:33.030
Student: How receptive
are the regulators to this idea?

01:05:33.030 --> 01:05:36.340
Prof: Well,
that's a good question.

01:05:36.340 --> 01:05:42.219
I talk to them now all the time
whereas I never did before.

01:05:42.219 --> 01:05:45.110
So I'm meeting Dudley tomorrow.
 

01:05:45.110 --> 01:05:46.869
He's the head of the New York
Fed.

01:05:46.869 --> 01:05:52.059
So I go there quite frequently
like once a month now.

01:05:52.059 --> 01:05:53.829
I'm on some panels.
 

01:05:53.829 --> 01:05:55.510
There are other academics going
too.

01:05:55.510 --> 01:05:59.085
So I didn't do that before,
so clearly they are paying

01:05:59.085 --> 01:06:00.300
attention to it.
 

01:06:00.300 --> 01:06:04.583
I think there are other people
saying that leverage is

01:06:04.583 --> 01:06:07.980
important, Soros,
being a famous hedge fund

01:06:07.980 --> 01:06:09.840
person who says it.
 

01:06:09.840 --> 01:06:12.405
There are other people saying
that you should reduce

01:06:12.405 --> 01:06:13.010
principal.
 

01:06:13.010 --> 01:06:15.358
Remember, I said that the way
to solve the housing foreclosure

01:06:15.358 --> 01:06:16.590
problem is reducing principal.
 

01:06:16.590 --> 01:06:19.219
They're now holding hearings in
Congress.

01:06:19.219 --> 01:06:23.038
I could have gone Tuesday to
testify, but I have already

01:06:23.038 --> 01:06:26.579
testified, but they're having
other hearings now.

01:06:26.579 --> 01:06:30.110
I didn't go because I was
teaching, but there were a lot

01:06:30.110 --> 01:06:33.061
of people who went,
and a lot of people said we

01:06:33.061 --> 01:06:34.860
should reduce principal.
 

01:06:34.860 --> 01:06:37.405
And a year ago when I was
saying that hardly anyone else

01:06:37.405 --> 01:06:39.302
was saying it,
although there were others,

01:06:39.302 --> 01:06:40.090
but very few.
 

01:06:40.090 --> 01:06:42.735
The people at my hedge fund,
we all pretty much see eye to

01:06:42.735 --> 01:06:45.429
eye on this and some other hedge
funds were saying that.

01:06:45.429 --> 01:06:48.036
But now, I think,
there's a growing consensus

01:06:48.036 --> 01:06:50.110
that we have to reduce
principal.

01:06:50.110 --> 01:06:51.070
What does that do?
 

01:06:51.070 --> 01:06:54.614
It makes the loan smaller
relative to the value of the

01:06:54.614 --> 01:06:55.150
house.
 

01:06:55.150 --> 01:06:57.693
In other words,
it reduces the leverage of

01:06:57.693 --> 01:06:58.500
homeowners.
 

01:06:58.500 --> 01:07:04.730
So we have to get back to a
credible level of leverage.

01:07:04.730 --> 01:07:08.347
So the bad news is that
although they're very receptive

01:07:08.347 --> 01:07:12.501
and although they're listening
carefully and they keep inviting

01:07:12.501 --> 01:07:15.985
me to speak I don't see much
signs that they're doing

01:07:15.985 --> 01:07:16.989
anything.
 

01:07:16.989 --> 01:07:19.552
And the one thing that they
should have done by now is

01:07:19.552 --> 01:07:20.809
collected all this data.
 

01:07:20.809 --> 01:07:23.699
So they should have gone to all
the big lenders and said,

01:07:23.699 --> 01:07:25.978
the Fed should have,
and said, "This is the

01:07:25.978 --> 01:07:28.789
margins we're charging on all
our different securities,

01:07:28.789 --> 01:07:31.643
here they are,"
and then the Fed would be able

01:07:31.643 --> 01:07:34.500
to monitor how much they were
going up and down.

01:07:34.500 --> 01:07:37.324
Now, a bunch of these lenders
themselves have also become

01:07:37.324 --> 01:07:40.349
excited about what I'm doing,
and they're starting to publish

01:07:40.349 --> 01:07:41.409
reports about it.
 

01:07:41.409 --> 01:07:44.429
So one, Credit Suisse,
for example,

01:07:44.429 --> 01:07:48.405
their research department now
thinks that a better measure of

01:07:48.405 --> 01:07:51.719
money is not just M1 and M2 and
all that stuff,

01:07:51.719 --> 01:07:55.760
but how many leveraged loans
are made in the Repo market,

01:07:55.760 --> 01:07:57.260
and they add that to the money
supply,

01:07:57.260 --> 01:07:59.733
and they think that gives them
a much better picture of the

01:07:59.733 --> 01:08:00.159
economy.
 

01:08:00.159 --> 01:08:02.518
So it's all sort of based on
these ideas and I think I got

01:08:02.518 --> 01:08:04.628
them interested in it,
or was one of the people that

01:08:04.628 --> 01:08:05.869
got them interested in it.
 

01:08:05.869 --> 01:08:08.648
But they aren't going to
publish their leverage numbers

01:08:08.648 --> 01:08:11.427
unless everybody else does
because why should they give

01:08:11.427 --> 01:08:12.920
away private information?
 

01:08:12.920 --> 01:08:15.393
Why should they say,
"We're lending to

01:08:15.393 --> 01:08:18.751
Ellington on slightly less
generous or more generous terms

01:08:18.751 --> 01:08:21.520
than we're lending to some other
guy."

01:08:21.520 --> 01:08:23.780
One of the two of us is going
to feel bad about it,

01:08:23.780 --> 01:08:25.500
and so they're not going to do
that.

01:08:25.500 --> 01:08:28.155
And so the government is the
only one that can get the

01:08:28.155 --> 01:08:29.460
information out of them.
 

01:08:29.460 --> 01:08:31.828
And the government shouldn't
say who are they lending to

01:08:31.828 --> 01:08:33.765
person by person,
they should give the average

01:08:33.765 --> 01:08:34.238
number.
 

01:08:34.238 --> 01:08:36.328
This is the average margin
they're charging people,

01:08:36.328 --> 01:08:39.930
the average number the banks in
general are charging people then

01:08:39.930 --> 01:08:42.789
you won't be revealing any
private information,

01:08:42.789 --> 01:08:44.300
giving away any secrets.
 

01:08:44.300 --> 01:08:47.905
So that's the worst news that
they're not collecting the data

01:08:47.905 --> 01:08:49.770
yet, and it's shocking to me.
 

01:08:49.770 --> 01:08:52.391
So I'm going to yell at Dudley
about that again Friday,

01:08:52.391 --> 01:08:54.966
but I've done it before,
so hopefully they're going to

01:08:54.966 --> 01:08:55.550
do that.
 

01:08:55.550 --> 01:08:57.527
They say they're going to do
that, so I believe they'll do

01:08:57.527 --> 01:08:57.770
that.
 

01:08:57.770 --> 01:09:00.155
And I believe that once they
have all these numbers they're

01:09:00.155 --> 01:09:01.720
going to start to think
differently.

01:09:01.720 --> 01:09:06.868
So there are all these
initiatives in Congress,

01:09:06.868 --> 01:09:09.252
and in the Fed,
and in the Treasury to try and

01:09:09.252 --> 01:09:11.529
monitor leverage and try to
regulate it,

01:09:11.529 --> 01:09:15.302
but every time they get down to
actually doing something they

01:09:15.302 --> 01:09:18.597
ask questions like you did,
what exactly should the rule

01:09:18.597 --> 01:09:21.715
be, and they seem paralyzed by
not being able to figure out the

01:09:21.715 --> 01:09:22.420
exact rule.
 

01:09:22.420 --> 01:09:25.247
But I think that's an
unnecessary paralysis because we

01:09:25.247 --> 01:09:28.449
don't have to have to the final
rule to start doing stuff.

01:09:28.449 --> 01:09:28.939
Yes?
 

01:09:28.939 --> 01:09:29.698
Student: I've got one
more question.

01:09:29.698 --> 01:09:32.380
How and who do you think should
be doing this?

01:09:32.380 --> 01:09:33.039
Prof: The Fed.
 

01:09:33.039 --> 01:09:34.408
The Fed has the power to do it.
 

01:09:34.408 --> 01:09:37.706
The Fed already regulates
margins on stocks,

01:09:37.706 --> 01:09:38.319
right?
 

01:09:38.319 --> 01:09:40.320
They set the margin at 50
percent or something,

01:09:40.320 --> 01:09:42.844
and so they could change that
and they have changed that in

01:09:42.844 --> 01:09:43.408
the past.
 

01:09:43.408 --> 01:09:47.060
So the Fed has the authority to
do that.

01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:49.510
The Fed did that after 9/11.
 

01:09:49.510 --> 01:09:52.210
They called everybody up and
said, right after 9/11,

01:09:52.210 --> 01:09:54.976
and said, "You cannot
change your margins,"

01:09:54.976 --> 01:09:56.840
and nobody changed their
margins.

01:09:56.840 --> 01:09:59.510
I mean if ever there was a day
when people were nervous and

01:09:59.510 --> 01:10:01.720
wanted to have a higher margin
it was on 9/12.

01:10:01.720 --> 01:10:03.939
Nobody changed their margins.
 

01:10:03.939 --> 01:10:10.461
So they've done it before,
but that's a pretty extreme

01:10:10.461 --> 01:10:11.199
day.
 

